OUR SCIENTIFIC GOAL, INSPIRED BY MAVEN SCIENCE QUESTION #1, IS TO INTEGRATE MAVEN DATA FROM MULTIPLE INSTRUMENTS TO DETERMINE HOW THE STATE OF THE DAYSIDE IONOSPHERE IS INFLUENCED BY THE NEUTRAL ATMOSPHERE, SOLAR FLUX, AND MAGNETIC ENVIRONMENT. THE PRIMARY WAY BY WHICH WE SHALL ADDRESS THIS GOAL IS TO TEST SIMPLE IONOSPHERIC PREDICTIONS IN THE TOPSIDE AND AT THE MAIN PEAK USING MAVEN DATA, ACCOMPANIED BY INTERPRETATION WITH THE BOSTON UNIVERSITY MARS IONOSPHERIC MODEL. THIS IS A NATURAL EXTENSION OF OUR CURRENT RESEARCH USING EXISTING DATASETS. ALMOST ALL NECESSARY DATA ARE INCLUDED IN THE MAVEN KEY PARAMETER FILES THAT DISSEMINATE USEABLE DATA AROUND THE MAVEN TEAM RAPIDLY AND REGULARLY. OUR WORK IS DIVIDED INTO FIVE TASKS, EACH OF WHICH ALSO DIRECTLY SUPPORTS MISSION OPERATIONS AND DECISION-MAKING. TASK A EXAMINES THE VERTICAL STRUCTURE OF THE TOPSIDE IONOSPHERE. TASK B EXAMINES THE COMPOSITION OF THE TOPSIDE IONOSPHERE. TASK C EXAMINES THE PEAK ELECTRON DENSITY. TASK D EXAMINES THE NEUTRAL PRESSURE AT THE IONOSPHERIC PEAK. TASK E, WHICH IS STRONGLY LINKED TO MISSION OPERATIONS, WILL SUPPORT SPACECRAFT OPERATIONS INSIDE THE ATMOSPHERE.

THE OVERARCHING SCIENTIFIC GOALS OF ACT-AMERICA ARE TO REDUCE UNCERTAINTIES IN BOTH MESOSCALE ATMOSPHERIC TRANSPORT AND BIOGENIC SURFACE CARBON FLUX ESTIMATES USING TARGETED AIRCRAFT MEASUREMENT CAMPAIGNS AND A REGIONAL INVERSION SYSTEM, AND TO THEREBY IMPROVE CONSTRAINT ON SURFACE BIOGENIC CARBON FLUXES AND ASSOCIATED ECOSYSTEM MODEL PARAMETERS. THESE IMPROVEMENTS WILL THEN BE TRANSFERRED TO A MULTI-YEAR, CONTINENTAL-SCALE INVERSION EFFORT THAT WILL ASSESS THE SENSITIVITY OF THE ORBITING CARBON OBSERVATORY COLUMN MEASUREMENTS TO REGIONAL VARIABILITY IN TROPOSPHERIC CO2. THE CORE INNOVATION OF ACT-AMERICA IS TO PERFORM REGIONAL SCALE ATMOSPHERIC INVERSIONS WITH AIRCRAFT MEASUREMENTS FROM TARGETED CAMPAIGNS. THE PROJECT HAS TWO KINDS OF FLIGHT PLANS, ONE FOCUSING ON WEATHER SYSTEMS SUCH AS MID-LATITUDE CYCLONES TO LEARN ABOUT TRANSPORT ERRORS, AND A SECOND FOCUSING ON FAIR WEATHER ATMOSPHERIC BOUNDARY LAYER MEASUREMENTS TO LEARN ABOUT ERRORS IN SURFACE BIOGENIC FLUXES. AIRCRAFT SAMPLING THAT DIRECTLY ADDRESSES ERRORS IN SURFACE BIOGENIC FLUXES WILL INVOLVE APPROXIMATELY THIRTY FLIGHTS IN TOTAL, ALLOCATED TO COVER THREE REGIONS (UPPER MIDWESTERN CROPLANDS, SOUTHCENTRAL FOREST AND AGRICULTURAL LANDS, AND MID-ATLANTIC TEMPERATE FORESTS, SEE FIGURE 1). THE SAMPLING DOMAIN FOR EACH REGION WILL SPAN A FEW HUNDRED KILOMETERS ON A SIDE AND WILL COVER FOUR SEASONS OF THE YEAR.

doc.ContractDescription: MASS-RADIUS-LUMINOSITY-ROTATION RELATIONSHIPS FOR M DWARF PLANET-HOSTING STARS IN PREPARATION FOR THE TESS, GAIA AND JWST ERA M DWARF STARS DOMINATE STELLAR POPULATIONS, BUT CURRENT STELLAR EVOLUTIONARY MODELS DO NOT ACCURATELY PREDICT THEIR FUNDAMENTAL PROPERTIES AS WELL AS THEY DO FOR SUN-LIKE STARS, WITH EFFECTS FROM RAPID ROTATION BEING A PROMINENT THEORY FOR THE DISCREPANCIES. THE DISCREPANCIES NEED TO BE RESOLVED SOON: BASED ON STATISTICS FROM NASA'S KEPLER MISSION, NASA'S FUTURE TESS MISSION WILL DISCOVER HUNDREDS IF NOT THOUSANDS OF TRANSITING TERRESTRIAL EXOPLANETS ORBITING NEARBY M DWARFS. ESA'S GAIA MISSION WILL PROVIDE PARALLAXES AND CORRESPONDING ABSOLUTE MAGNITUDES FOR THE TESS M DWARF TARGETS. IT IS CRITICALLY IMPORTANT TO DEVELOP ACCURATE AND PRECISE MASSRADIUS - LUMINOSITY - ROTATION RELATIONSHIPS FOR M DWARFS IN PREPARATION FOR TESS AND GAIA, SINCE ACCURATE RELATIONSHIPS ARE REQUIRED TO DETERMINE THE RADII AND EQUILIBRIUM TEMPERATURES OF TESS'S EXOPLANET DISCOVERIES TO HIGH PRECISION. IN THE FUTURE, NASA'S JWST MISSION WILL BE ABLE TO MEASURE THE ATMOSPHERIC CONSTITUENTS OF TERRESTRIAL PLANETS THAT TRANSIT M DWARFS, BUT AT A SIGNIFICANT COST IN TELESCOPE TIME. THEREFORE, THE JWST TARGETS MUST BE CHOSEN CAREFULLY FROM TESS'S DISCOVERIES, AND THEY REQUIRE THE BEST POSSIBLE KNOWLEDGE OF THE EXOPLANETS' RADII AND EQUILIBRIUM TEMPERATURES, WHICH IN TURN REQUIRES THE BEST POSSIBLE KNOWLEDGE OF THEIR M DWARF HOST STARS. WE PROPOSE TO CONDUCT A THREE-YEAR, MULTI-TELESCOPE OBSERVING CAMPAIGN TO MEASURE MASSES, RADII, DISTANCES, AND INDIVIDUAL INFRARED MAGNITUDES OF 40 NEW M DWARF ECLIPSING BINARIES DISCOVERED BY THE INVESTIGATORS IN ARCHIVAL KEPLER DATA. THE CATALOG NEARLY TRIPLES THE NUMBER OF M DWARF ECLIPSING BINARIES KNOWN TO DATE. BY COMBINING ULTRA-PRECISE PUBLICLY-AVAILABLE ARCHIVAL KEPLER PHOTOMETRY, DOUBLE-LINED SPECTROSCOPIC RADIAL VELOCITY MEASUREMENTS, ADAPTIVE OPTICS IMAGING, PARALLAX OBSERVATIONS, AND INFRARED ECLIPSE OBSERVATIONS, WE WILL MEASURE THE MASSES, RADII, DISTANCES AND INDIVIDUAL ABSOLUTE INFRARED MAGNITUDES FOR THE INDIVIDUAL COMPONENTS OF THE M-DWARF BINARY STARS WITH UNPRECEDENTED ACCURACY AND PRECISION. THE INVESTIGATORS WILL USE THE MEASUREMENTS TO CREATE NEW, EMPIRICAL MASS-RADIUS-LUMINOSITY-ROTATION RELATIONSHIPS FOR M DWARFS. THESE RELATIONSHIPS WILL SETTLE LONG-STANDING CONTROVERSIES OVER THE ROLE OF ROTATION AND MAGNETIC ACTIVITY ON M DWARF PROPERTIES. THE RELATIONSHIPS WILL BE USED TO DETERMINE THE RADII AND EQUILIBRIUM TEMPERATURES OF NEARBY TERRESTRIAL EXOPLANETS THAT TRANSIT M DWARFS AS DISCOVERED BY NASA'S TRANSITING EXOPLANET SURVEY SATELLITE (TESS) MISSION, AND TO CHOSE THOSE TARGETS TO STUDY IN DETAIL WITH JWST.

doc.ContractDescription: THE GOAL OF OUR WORK IS TO IDENTIFY EARLY AND LATE EFFECTS OF SPACE RADIATION ON THE CONNECTIONS BETWEEN NERVE CELLS IN THE BRAIN, SYNAPSES, INFLAMMATION AND COGNITION SO THAT ONE CAN ASSESS THE CNS RISK TO FUTURE ASTRONAUTS INVOLVED IN LONG-DURATION LUNAR MISSIONS AND OR A MISSION TO MARS. THESE EARLY CHANGES, ALONG WITH CHANGES IN BRAIN INFLAMMATION THAT MAY RELAY SIGNALS BETWEEN CELLS IN THE BRAIN AND BLOOD FLOW, MAY HELP DEFINE THOSE INDIVIDUALS AT RISK FOR DEVELOPING LONG-TERM LEARNING AND MEMORY PROBLEMS. OUR STUDIES WILL UTILIZE NORMAL, WILDTYPE MICE AND A GENETIC MOUSE MODEL OF ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE. FEMALE AND MALE 4 MONTH OLD MICE WILL BE IRRADIATED ONCE WITH VARYING DOSES OF HEAVY IONS OR PROTONS AND EXAMINED 2 OR 10 MONTHS LATER. CHRONIC DOSING WILL BE COMPARED WITH A SINGLE DOSE FOR LONG-TERM EFFECTS AS WELL. MICE WILL UNDERGO PET IMAGING FOR BRAIN INFLAMMATION AND BLOOD FLOW, AND BEHAVIORAL TESTING BEFORE BEING EUTHANIZED. WE WILL PERFORM A CLOSE-UP INSPECTION OF SYNAPSES, ALZHEIMER'S AMYLOID PLAQUES, NEURON LOSS, AND INFLAMMATION IN THE BRAIN.
